BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/ca3314f0-f716-4500-81fe-02298d394d2c.jpg
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260515T101925Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for a walkthrough of the herbal gardens at the National Centre for Biological Sciences (NCBS) campus - a serene green spot nestled between a maze of labs\, and beloved by students\, staff\, faculty\, and resident cats alike.\n\nIts roots trace to a ground breaking exhibit in 2008 where former cell biologist and scholar of Indian botanical-medicinal traditions\, Annamma Spudich\, brought 50 medicinal plants described in the Hortus Malabaricus and planted a living exhibition in its spot. This exhibition\, titled "Such Treasure and Rich Merchandize: Indian Botanical knowledge in 16th and 17th Century European Books"\, was not only a unique collaboration between horticulturalists\, artists\, and historians\, but also one of the many growing efforts by the institution\, to reflect on history and society.\n\nAlmost two decades later\, the garden thrives\, but how much of a curation remains? And how have those initial ideas grown? Discover its story and learn about the Archives at NCBS and their work to document contemporary botanical records amongst its larger catalogue of history of science.\n\nThis programme is in collaboration with NCBS\, and in conjunction with MAP's ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire.
DTEND:20260530T080000Z
DTSTART:20260530T053000Z
SUMMARY:Such Treasure Revived: A Garden Walk and Visit to the Archives
UID:1278@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/such-treasure-revived-a-garden-walk-and-visit-to-the-archives/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/POP.32795-scaled.jpg
CATEGORIES: Featuring,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260521T075428Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Leaflet from Hortus Indicus Malabaricus depicting an illustration titled 'Cattu-tirpali’\, Hendrik van Rheede\, Itty Achudan\, 1686\, Copper plate engraving on handmade laid paper\, H. 40 cm\, W. 51.3 cm\nFor centuries India was the nexus of a global trade in spices\, medicines\, dyes\, unguents and perfumes—high‑value goods whose value rested on deep\, native knowledge of plants and healing. In this online talk\, renowned researcher Dr. Annamma Spudich traces how archaeological finds and trade records from the first millennium onwards reveal India’s sophisticated botanical and medical systems\, and why by the Middle Ages “India trade was the backbone of the international economy.”\n\nLearn how the late‑15th‑century European search for direct sea routes brought Spain\, Portugal\, and later the Dutch and British\, into India\, and how\, finding their own medical knowledge inadequate for the tropics\, turned to Indian physicians and botanical expertise. Dr Spudich will examine these European documents from the 16th–19th centuries that recorded Indian medicinal\, agricultural and horticultural knowledge\, and show how these encounters broadened Western science\, inspired artists and poets and reshaped global history.\n\nThis online talk is in conjunction with MAP’s ongoing exhibition\, Paper Gardens: Art\, Botany and Empire\, bringing together over a hundred botanical illustrations\, tracing encounters between plants\, artists\, and institutions\, and reanimating the networks of labour and imagination that have built our understanding of the natural world.
DTEND:20260531T150000Z
DTSTART:20260531T140000Z
SUMMARY:In Search for Knowledge and Riches
UID:1287@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/in-search-for-knowledge-and-riches/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/DSC00963-scaled-e1778247442455.jpg
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260512T063004Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for an immersive and accessible experience specially designed for people with visual disabilities at MAP’s Living Botanical followed by an interactive workshop with artist Mohit Mahato.\n\nThe session will begin with a guided walkthrough of the garden\, where participants will experience and engage with a variety of plants through touch\, smell\, observation\, and discussion. Following the walkthrough\, Mohit will lead a workshop exploring plants in greater depth\, including their behaviour\, medicinal value\, the types of soil they grow in\, the climates they thrive in\, and which parts of the plants are considered most useful or valuable.\n\nMohit will also share insights into his artistic practice and how nature influences his work. Drawing from his experience as an artist\, he will speak about how he uses different parts of trees and plants within his art-making process\, creating connections between ecology\, material\, texture\, and artistic expression.\n\nThis session invites participants with visual disabilities to connect with nature not only through sensory exploration and learning\, but also through creativity and artistic imagination.
DTEND:20260524T113000Z
DTSTART:20260524T093000Z
SUMMARY:Scent\, Soil\, and Art: An Immersive Experience
UID:1272@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/scent-soil-and-art-an-immersive-experience/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/RK_SOT-InstalViews-web-17.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260520T050653Z
DESCRIPTION:MAP's ongoing exhibition\, Beneath the Turning Sky explores how we find our place in this vast\, unfolding universe. How do our choices shape the world\, our communities\, and all others with whom we share the world?\nThis label-making workshop\, led by Priya Chauhan from the MAP team\, invites you to reflect on your own relationship with the world around you\, through the powerful potential of the arts. With insights on best practices in museum label writing\, participants get to create their own\, fostering a personal connection with the artworks.\n\nCome and uncover the layered meanings within artworks. Join us for a journey of observation\, reflection and creative expression.\nThis event is a part of the International Museum Day programming.
DTEND:20260524T080000Z
DTSTART:20260524T060000Z
SUMMARY:Museum Label-Writing Workshop
UID:1284@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/museum-label-writing-workshop/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Website-cover-images-new-2026-04-22T104009.698.png
CATEGORIES:Youth Engagement,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260519T095318Z
DESCRIPTION:What does vulnerability look like? What does care feel like?\nThese are the questions that artist Afra Eisma leaves us with in Warrior Garments.\n\nJoin us for a three-part series of reflective feminist reading sessions\, developed in collaboration with Zubaan and  facilitated by Laxmi Murthy. Together\, we will explore gender-based violence—its lived realities\, and the possibilities of resistance\, solidarity\, and healing. Through stories\, essays\, and personal reflections\, you are invited to engage with the exhibition at your own pace\, in a space that encourages listening\, sharing\, and care.\n\nNote:\n\n- This is the second session in a series presented alongside Warrior Garments. Each session is self-contained\, but we encourage participants to attend all three.\n\n- The next session will take place on June 21\, 2026.\n\n- Reading materials for each will be shared after registration.\n\nTrigger Warning: The sessions may include discussions on sexual violence.
DTEND:20260530T073000Z
DTSTART:20260530T053000Z
SUMMARY:Holding Space: Feminist Reading Circle
UID:1281@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/holding-space-feminist-reading-circle-2/
END:VEVENT
END:VCALENDAR